Date: SUMMARY  
Abstract: Autoconfiscation is the process of converting a software package to using GNU Autoconf, Automake, and Libtool. These tools assist in automating software configuration for packages that need to build and run on many platforms. 13 They do so by providing developers and maintainers with a set of prepackaged and flexibly modifiable tests for various conditions that may differ across systems. This paper describes my efforts at converting Amd, the Berkeley-based automounter 4,5 and its assorted utilities, to be automatically configurable. The new package is called Am-utils, is more portable, flexible, and its large code base cleaner. Consequently, it is easier now to port Amd to new platforms or add new features with a high probability that the changes will work well across all existing ports. However, the initial process of autoconfiscating was long and tedious. Some of the reasons were specific to the tools used, but a few were due to Amd's specific peculiarities mostly relating to being a user level multiple implementation file server. Autoconf could not solve all of the portability issues that Amd required. 
